        "creation_date": 1429090612,
        "answer_count": 4,
        "title": "JLabel&#39;s Set Location inside for not moving smoothly",
        "body": "<p>i'm using a label for a little sprite for some testing that i'm doing, but i want to move the sprite 10 pixels per keypress. Now, i can do that, but now i'm trying to make it move the 10 pixels smoothly, so i tried the next code:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for(int i = 0; i &lt; 100; i++){\n        x++;\n        container.setLocation(x, y);\n        System.out.println(x);\n        try {\n            Thread.sleep(10);\n        } catch (InterruptedException e) {\n            e.printStackTrace();\n        }\n    }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now the problem is that, the sprite only moves when the for cycle ends, but the console shows the X value changing for each iteration. Any thoughts/help?\nThanks!<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 29646727,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "swing",
            "for-loop",
            "jlabel"
        ],
        "score": 1,
        "accepted_answer_id": 29647294,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 519,
        "last_edit_date": 1429092090
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/EkU05.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 4551635,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3696632,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3696632/burak",
                "reputation": 608,
                "display_name": "Burak.",
                "accept_rate": 94
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1429093540,
            "creation_date": 1429092191,
            "body": "<p>I suggest you to take a look at how to animate a JComponent using <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/javax/swing/Timer.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Swing Timer class<\/a>, instead of for loop. You can find various tutorials about <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/misc/timer.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">how to use Swing Timer<\/a>. Here, to briefly explain, you are blocking <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/concurrency/dispatch.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">EDT(Event Dispatch Thread)<\/a> which operates the graphical side of the Java. Whenever you want to make a constant and smooth flow in your animations, make sure that <em>you never block the EDT<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT:<\/strong> Here is the demonstration of the usage of Swing Timer Class:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.awt.EventQueue;\nimport java.awt.event.ActionEvent;\nimport java.awt.event.ActionListener;\n\nimport javax.swing.JFrame;\nimport javax.swing.JLabel;\nimport javax.swing.Timer;\n\npublic class AnimationTrial extends JFrame {\n\n    private final int DELAY = 10;\n\n    private Timer timer;\n    private int x, y;\n    private JLabel label;\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        EventQueue.invokeLater( new Runnable () {\n\n            @Override\n            public void run() {\n                new AnimationTrial();\n            }\n\n        });\n    }\n\n    public AnimationTrial()\n    {\n        setSize(500, 500);\n        x = 50;\n        y = 50;\n\n        label = new JLabel(\"They see me movin' they hatin'!\");\n\n        timer = new Timer( DELAY, new ActionListener()\n        {\n\n            @Override\n            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent arg0) {\n\n                x++;\n                label.setLocation(x, y);    \n            }\n\n        });\n        timer.start();\n\n        getContentPane().add(label);\n        pack();\n        setVisible (true);\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 29647294,
            "question_id": 29646727,
            "last_edit_date": 1429093540
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/snzI5.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 3403175,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2854908,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2854908/libik",
                "reputation": 23069,
                "display_name": "libik",
                "accept_rate": 95
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1429091009,
            "creation_date": 1429091009,
            "body": "<p>If you dont create new Thread, the user interface runs on the same thread as its method.<\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore your for-cycle is fired after some action and thread cant do anything else until it ends.<\/p>\n\n<p>Solution : Create your own class, pass the JLabel or the whole form as parameter in constructor, implement threading and run it as new thread.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 29646858,
            "question_id": 29646727
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11d02948741b436f70421b07ffb9baa5?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 43420,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 126945,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/126945/gnoupi",
                "reputation": 4754,
                "display_name": "Gnoupi",
                "accept_rate": 85
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1429091517,
            "creation_date": 1429091517,
            "body": "<p>I'd suggest you give a look to the <a href=\"https://java.net/projects/timingframework/pages/Home\" rel=\"nofollow\">Timing Framework<\/a>, if you want to do something close to an animation in Swing. It could help you, depending on your general need.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 29647028,
            "question_id": 29646727
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://graph.facebook.com/904188036299090/picture?type=large",
                "account_id": 6070815,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4739715,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4739715/frank-andres",
                "reputation": 146,
                "display_name": "Frank Andres"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1429092085,
            "creation_date": 1429092085,
            "body": "<p>If you want other sprites to move in sync with your sprite you can create a <code>TimerTask<\/code> and use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Timer.html#scheduleAtFixedRate%28java.util.TimerTask,%20java.util.Date,%20long%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">scheduleAtFixedRate()<\/a>. Your <code>TimerTask<\/code> would then be responsible for moving all sprites and redrawing everything that was part of the moving like the <code>JPanel<\/code> in the background and the sprites. <\/p>\n\n<p>To make your code snippet work you would have to add redrawing of the Background and the sprite after setting the location but I would advise against that approach as it can easily lead to badly designed code where you create one God Class that does everything.<\/p>\n\n<p>The <code>TimerTask<\/code> approach should also be more precise if the calculations need a bit time as it tries to have the same time between 2 calls where the approach with the sleeping thread can easily lead to different delays if the calculations are finished earlier or later.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 29647251,
            "question_id": 29646727
        }
    ],
